\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Boundary Protection and Architecture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Network Administrator shall monitor and control communications at the external managed interfaces to the system and at key internal managed interfaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Managed Interfaces
\series default
:
 Connections to external networks (Internet) or external information systems shall occur only through managed interfaces (e.g.,
 firewalls,
 proxies,
 gateways) arranged in accordance with the security architecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Deny-by-Default
\series default
:
 Boundary protection devices shall be configured to deny all traffic (inbound and outbound) by default and allow only those services and ports explicitly authorized by the IT Director for business need.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Split Tunneling Prohibition
\series default
:
 For all remote access sessions connecting to the County network,
 the Systems Administrator shall configure the remote access mechanism to disable "split tunneling." All network traffic from the remote device must be routed through the County’s managed boundary protection devices for inspection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
DMZ Implementation
\series default
:
 Publicly accessible system components (e.g.,
 web servers) shall reside in a Demilitarized Zone (DMZ),
 physically or logically separated from internal organizational networks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Denial of Service (DoS)
\series default
:
 The Network Administrator shall configure boundary devices to detect and mitigate DoS attacks by implementing rate limiting and traffic filtering to reduce attack traffic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Transmission Confidentiality and Integrity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Encryption In-Transit
\series default
:
 CJI and PII transmitted outside a physically secure location (as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
) shall be encrypted.
 Wireless transmission of CJI is prohibited unless encrypted using a FIPS-validated module.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Cryptographic Standards
\series default
:
 Encryption mechanisms for data in-transit shall use cryptographic modules validated under the Cryptographic Module Validation Program (CMVP) as compliant with FIPS 140-3 (or FIPS 140-2 until sunset date of Sept 21,
 2026).
 The symmetric cipher key strength shall be at least 128-bit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Session Authenticity
\series default
:
 Systems shall protect the authenticity of communications sessions (e.g.,
 TLS 1.2 or higher) to prevent Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) attacks or session hijacking.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Network Disconnect (Idle Timeout)
\series default
:
 To limit exposure of open sessions,
 the Network Administrator shall configure VPN and remote access gateways to automatically terminate connections after fifteen (15) minutes of inactivity.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Exemption
\series default
:
 As defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 remote access sessions utilizing certificate-based authentication on devices located within a secure Criminal Justice Conveyance (e.g.,
 patrol vehicles) are exempt from this timeout to ensure officer safety.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Protection of Information at Rest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall protect the confidentiality and integrity of information at rest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJI Encryption
\series default
:
 CJI stored on digital media (servers,
 workstations,
 mobile devices,
 external drives) outside of a physically secure location shall be encrypted using FIPS-validated cryptographic modules (FIPS 140-2/3) with a minimum 128-bit key strength.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Mobile Devices
\series default
:
 All County-issued laptops,
 tablets,
 and smartphones shall have full-disk encryption enabled prior to deployment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Cryptographic Key Management
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall manage cryptographic keys to secure the key lifecycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Generation
\series default
:
 Keys shall be generated using FIPS-validated Random Number Generators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Distribution
\series default
:
 Keys shall be distributed via secure methods that prevent unauthorized disclosure (e.g.,
 encrypted channels).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Storage
\series default
:
 Unencrypted keys shall not be stored on the same system or media as the encrypted data they protect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Destruction
\series default
:
 Keys shall be destroyed/zeroized immediately when they are no longer needed or when the association with the authorized user/entity is terminated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Collaborative Computing Devices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To prevent unauthorized remote surveillance,
 the Systems Administrator shall configure systems to prohibit the remote activation of collaborative computing devices (cameras,
 microphones).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Indication of Use
\series default
:
 Devices shall provide a physical or on-screen indication when collaborative devices are active.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Disablement
\series default
:
 Users accessing CJI via a workstation with a built-in camera/microphone must physically cover or logically disable the device if the environment is not secure or if the device is not required for the immediate task.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Secure Name/Address Resolution (DNS)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Network Administrator shall ensure the integrity of the Domain Name System (DNS).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Forgery Protection
\series default
:
 Recursive resolvers shall be configured to request and validate DNS Security Extensions (DNSSEC) signatures to verify the authenticity of DNS responses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Fault Tolerance
\series default
:
 The County shall maintain at least two geographically separated DNS servers (or utilize a redundant cloud DNS provider) to ensure availability.
\end_layout

